answers.body_markdown:
Change the relationship on the **Minister** model and remove the count.  That count in the relationship will screw up the eager loading.  So:

    function active(){
       return $this-&gt;hasMany( Officer::class)-&gt;where(&#39;state&#39;, &#39;active&#39; );
    }

Now you can use a closure on the `with()` method and pull that secondary relationship and get the count using the [Larvel method][1] `withCount()`.

Something like this:
    
     $nation = Nation::where(&#39;id&#39;, $nation_id)-&gt;with([&#39;ministers&#39; =&gt; function($query){
            $query-&gt;withCount(&#39;active&#39;);
        }])-&gt;get();

It should be eager loaded and you can access the active count via the `$nation` object and its relation, `ministers`:

     $activeOfficers = $nation-&gt;ministers-&gt;first()-&gt;active_count;

This will give you the active officers for the first minister for that nation.  If you want to total all of them, easy to loop:

    $totalActiveOfficersForNation = 0;
    foreach($nation-&gt;ministers as $minister){
        $totalActiveOfficersForNation += $minister-&gt;active_count;
    }

There are other ways to count columns, but this is pretty straightforward.

Hope this helps.


  [1]: https://laravel.com/docs/5.7/eloquent-relationships#counting-related-models

